HOSPITAL COURSE:  Patient remained in-house and was noted to
have peak in her creatinine up to 2.3 over the weekend.
Patient had urine studies sent.  The urine FENa was
calculated at 0.3% consistent with dehydration.  Urinalysis
was otherwise normal and a renal ultrasound was otherwise
normal.  No hydronephrosis or obstruction.  Patient received
two 250 cc boluses of normal saline and had her Foley
replaced for better in and out monitoring, and patient's
creatinine improved the following day to 1.4.

Otherwise, the patient is doing well.  Plans to continue to
follow her renal function likely secondary to overdiuresis
and dehydration with some diarrhea.  Patient is also noted to
have increasing amounts of diarrhea over the weekend.
Clostridium difficile were sent, which are pending to this
date, and otherwise seems stable and changes were consistent
with patient being dehydrated.

Chronic cough/anterior mediastinal mass:  Patient had a CT of
her chest done to better evaluate as she had one episode of
hemoptysis, and with her chronic cough since [**Month (only) 768**].
Patient's CT of the chest showed diffuse hazy ground-glass
opacity effecting the right lung to a greater extent in the
left consistent with pulmonary edema or atypical infectious
process or pulmonary hemorrhage.  Also evidence of prior
granulomatous disease and a lobulated mass in the anterior
mediastinum, which likely represents a thymoma and a small
hiatal hernia.

Patient was re-evaluated by the Hematology/Oncology service.
They felt they needed tissue samples to further diagnose, but
that this was less consistent with a lymphoma picture.
Patient was seen by the CT Surgery service for possible
biopsy or excision.  They are currently reviewing the films
to decide whether a simple biopsy or excision is needed if
this is an infiltrative process.  Patient will continue to
have this worked up as an outpatient as patient will require
being on aspirin and Plavix after her recent stent.  At least
for two weeks, she will have to stay on it preferably for
four months.  This anticoagulation issue can be further
evaluated after review of films and evaluation by CT Surgery.

Anemia:  The patient's hematocrit remained stable over the
weekend, and she will continue to have outpatient followup
with gastroenterologist and anemia, and continue her iron
repletion.

Decreased ejection fraction:  Patient with an EF of 30-35%
and posterolateral akinesis.  Patient was originally started
on lisinopril and started back on her Lasix and
spironolactone regimen.  These were held in light of her
acute renal failure and overdiuresis.  These can eventually
be restarted once creatinine are stable at rehab.

DISCHARGE DIAGNOSES:
1. Inferior myocardial infarction.
2. Decreased ejection fraction.
3. Fluid overload.
4. Acute renal failure.
5. Anterior mediastinal mass.
6. Anemia.
7. Cough.
8. Diarrhea.

DISCHARGE MEDICATIONS:  Will be dictated at time of
discharge.

DISCHARGE FOLLOWUP:  Patient is to followup with her PCP [**Last Name (NamePattern4) **]
[**7-29**] days.  Patient is to followup with cardiologist chosen
by her PCP [**Last Name (NamePattern4) **] [**2-22**] weeks.  Patient is to have a repeat stress
in [**6-27**] weeks to re-evaluate her RCA lesion.  Patient is to
followup with CT Surgery for further evaluation of her
anterior mediastinal mass.  Patient is to followup with her
hematologist for her anemia.  Patient is to followup with an
outpatient gastroenterologist for further workup of her
guaiac-positive stools.

ADDENDUM:  The infant was born at a birth weight of 2745
grams at 35 and 3/7 weeks gestation. His discharge weight was
2715 grams at 37 and [**1-22**] corrected gestational age. Day of
life 14 was the date of discharge.

1. RESPIRATORY: The infant was transferred from the [**Hospital 10627**] Well Baby Nursery to the NICU due to shallow
   breathing and low oxygen saturations on room air. The
   infant's evaluation included a chest x-ray which revealed
   a complete whiteout of both lung fields in addition to his
   physical findings of shallow breathing and some
   retractions. Diagnosis of RDS was made. He was intubated
   and given surfactant and then weaned to CPAP. He was
   eventually weaned to room air by around day 8 of life. His
   respiratory issue was presumed to be clinical pneumonia,
   although no cultures were positive. Antibiotics were
   continued empirically for 7 days. Clinical, his
   respiratory issues resolved and were normal throughout the
   latter half of his neonatal course. He always had a normal
   cardiovascular exam.

1. HEMATOLOGY: The infant had hyperbilirubinemia with a peak
   bilirubin of around 15.5; treated with phototherapy
   blanket. This resolved.

1. INFECTIOUS DISEASE: Sepsis evaluation was negative,
   resolved.

1. GI AND NUTRITION: Bloody GI aspirate felt to be secondary
   to maternal blood which the infant swallowed after
   delivery. The infant was treated with ranitidine for 72
   hours. No further problems with feeding or upper GI
   bleeding. This again was felt secondary to swallowed
   maternal blood. The infant had a stable nutritional and GI
   status since then.

1. IMMATURE FEEDING: With the baby's mouth prematurity he
   required some gavage feeds and working with developing all
   p.o. feeds which he had at the time of discharge.


1. OTHER: The infant was circumcised. No problems on the day
   of discharge. Also, the infant's hearing screen revealed
   bilateral referral. The parents are to follow up with
   audiology evaluation after discharge. VNA nursing will be
   involved as well.

1. SUMMARY: A 35.5 week gestation infant who had respiratory
   concerns felt to be possibly secondary to immature lungs
   and/or pneumonia; treated empirically. The remainder of
   the course was one of becoming more mature with feedings,
   which occurred.

TITLE: OROPHARYNGEAL VIDEOFLUOROSCOPIC SWALLOWING EVALUATION
   EVALUATION:
   An oral and pharyngeal swallowing videofluoroscopy was performed today
   in collaboration with Radiology.  Thin liquid, Nectar-thick liquid,
   pureed consistency barium, one cookie coated with barium and one barium
   pill were administered. Results follow:
   ORAL PHASE:
   The oral phase was remarkable for moderately reduced bolus control with
   premature spillover of thin and nectar thick liquid to the valleculae
   and pyriform sinuses prior to the swallow.  Despite nearly edentulous
   status, pt able to chew and clear cookie within less than 30 seconds.
   Notable for moderate oral cavity residue after the first swallow,
   required [**12-21**] swallows to clear each bite/sip from the oral cavity.
   PHARYNGEAL PHASE:
   Notable for a large glob of secretions which were sitting in the
   pharynx (coating pharyngeal wall) prior to PO intake.  Pt tried to
   cough and clear this glob multiple times without success.  Yankauer
   suctioning also not successful and resulted in significant agitation.
   Physiologically, the pharyngeal phase of the swallow was remarkable for
   mildly reduced epiglottic deflection and mildly reduced bolus
   propulsion with mild-moderate residue in the vallecuale and pyriform
   sinuses following the initial swallow.  This cleared with repeat
   swallows.  Otherwise WNL for swallow initiation, palatal elevation and
   laryngeal valve closure.
   ASPIRATION/PENETRATION:
   During the course of the evaluation, the mucous in pharyngeal cavity
   became loosened and coated with barium material.  This subsequently
   dripped into the laryngeal vestibule and pt coughed, attempting to
   clear.  There were no other episodes of laryngeal penetration or
   aspiration of actual PO boluses.
   SUMMARY:
   Pt presents with mild oropharyngeal dysphagia complicated by a coating
   of secretions on the pharyngeal wall which loosened during the
   evaluation and dripped into the airway.  Pt was unable to spontaneously
   clear this and was unable to tolerate suctioning [**12-20**] agitation.  Other
   than this secretion issue, pt had no laryngeal penetration or
   aspiration on today's evaluation.  He appears safe for his baseline
   diet of regular solids and thin liquids with aspiration precautions.
   He will benefit from distant supervision with PO to maintain
   precautions, but likely will not tolerate direct assistance with
   intake.  Please reconsult if there are further concerns for aspiration
   of food/liquid or other dysphagia and a repeat evaluation can be
   performed.
   This swallowing pattern correlates to a Dysphagia Outcome Severity
   Scale (DOSS) rating of 5, mild dysphagia.
   RECOMMENDATIONS:
   1. PO diet: regular solids, thin liquids
   2. PO meds whole with thin liquids
   3. TID oral care
   4. Distant supervision with meals to maintain aspiration precautions
   and assist with self-feed as willing.
   5. Please page/reconsult if we can be of further assistance.
   These recommendations were shared with the patient, the nurse and the
   medical team.

86 y/o F with PMHx of COPD on home O2 s/p recent admission to [**Hospital1 3772**] for COPD exacerbation who was transferred to [**Hospital1 1**] on [**1-30**]
   from [**Location (un) **] in the setting of respiratory distress.
   .
   According to patient, the night prior to presenting to [**Location (un) **], she
   slept with her oxygen disconnected. That morning, she felt
   significantly SOB and presented to [**Hospital3 **]. At [**Location (un) **] she was
   hypoxic to the 60s on RA which improve to 92-95 on 5L. She was also
   tachycardic with HRs in 120s-140s and EKG showed NSTTW changes. CXR
   showed a possible RML infiltrate, labs revealed leukocytosis to 24K,
   CK/Trop 56/0.16. She received Solumedrol, Levaquin, and Amiodarone and
   was transferred to MICU at [**Hospital1 1**] for futher care.
   .
   At [**Hospital1 1**], the hypoxia was felt due to a combination of COPD flare
   precipitated by a prolonged period without her regular oxygen as well
   as possible flash pulmonary edema in the setting of htn and
   tachycardia. She was initially treated for bronchitis vs pna with
   vanc/zosyn and was quickly changed to levofloxacin. She also received
   20 mg of IV lasix. She was continued on a slow prednisone taper and
   her symptoms slowly improved and she was weaned to her baseline 3LNC.
   Her elevated cardiac enzymes were attributed to demand ischemia in the
   setting of tachycardia and hypoxia. Cardiac enzymes trended down and pt
   remained asymptomatic. ECHO showed mildly depressed LVEF of 50% and
   apical RV akinesis.  Pt was transferred to the floor and continued to
   have issues with sob, anxiety and issues with constipation.
   .
   Over the last 2-3 days, pt was noted to have hct drop and intermittent
   tachycardia of unclear etiology.  Pt has been describing epigastric
   pain & sore throat for the last three days. Overnight, she developped
   worsening epigastric pain & NF performed an EKG that was essentially
   unchanged, CK/MB were flat and hct of 20.  In the morning, hemolysis
   labs returned negative and it was discovered that the patient had been
   having guaic positive stools and MICU was called to evaluate.

   trending down.  Chest pain subsided w/o any intervention.  Pt given neb

   55yo female with resolving ARDS and H. flu bacteremia presents for
   re-admission to the MICU for increased O2 requirement, afebrile for
   past four days.
   .
   # ARDS
 Patient has documented dead space of 84%. Patient had
   completed a course of treatment for known H. flu bacteremia with
   azithromycin, 7 day empiric course of meropenem. After worsening around
   [**12-20**], patient was started on vanc/zosyn. On [**12-24**] and [**12-25**] [**Female First Name (un) **] was done
   bilaterally for concern of empyema. Patient was trached on [**12-25**]. Patient
   continues to be tachypneic in the 30-40s with an element of anxiety.
   Multiple bronchs have been done and there does not appear to be a
   current PNA since there are not any secretions. Concern for
   inflammatory causes less in the setting of no bronchial fluid or
   peripheral eosinophillia. Differential includes infectious cause vs.
   BOOP. There has been a poor response to antbiotics and no secretions on
   bronch argues against PNA. Patients peribronchovascular pattern could
   be consistent with BOOP over typical ARDS picture. BOOP would require
   treatment with steroids and until clear diagnosis is made difficult to
   justify steroids in the setting of possible infectious cause.
   Differentiation of the etiologies of the ARDS would require tissue bx.
   This would require VATS but the patient does not have enough lung
   reserve to take down one lung for the procedure. The patient
s clinical
   resp pattern is consistent with pulmonary fibrosis vs. rind. IP did not
   feel thoracentesis would be beneficial. Patient got PSV valve placed on
   [**12-30**], resp status improving.
   - Continue periods of PMV, trach mask and PSV 5/5, avoiding resp
   fatigue
   - patient would not be a good candidate for vasodialtors such as
   slidenafil or NO
   - will not tx with steroids
   .

 WBC stable, unclear etiology for patient's
   fever and leukocytosis.  Blood cultures NTD, VRE in urine but not
   likely source of infection. Cardiac echo, no evidence of endocarditis.

   thoracentesis with no infectious organism identified.  Derm bx was

   large right pelvic sidewall mass obstructing her ureter and multiple
   enlarged lymph nodes. She had a stent placed in her right ureter and LN
   biopsy revealed recurrence of her grade 3b follicular cell lymphoma.

   study protocol #DF 09-111.

   IMPRESSION: Abnormal portable EEG due to the slow background and due to
   the bursts of frequent mixed frequency generalized slowing, some with
   very sharp features and with occasional bursts of an attenuation of the
   background in all areas. These findings indicate a widespread and
   mildly severe encephalopathy affecting both cortical and subcortical
   structures. The rhythmic left temporal slowing associated with the
   patient's movements raise the possibility of a focal seizure (with
   spread), but these bursts were relatively brief. The recording does not
   establish definite diagnosis, and additional recording, preferably
   including times when the patient is not resting on her side, could be
   helpful with diagnosis.

   74-year-old woman with recurrent follicular cell lymphoma who presented
   for induction with protocol Ofatumumab/ICE and was transferred to the
   ICU for acute mental status changes and fever.
   .
   # Acute MS changes: Improved since admission. Etiology unclear, though
   concerning for [**Name (NI) 8017**] toxicity given recent completion of chemo regimen
   with known neurotoxicity. Infection also likely contributing with
   fever, tachycardia and tachypnea.  CXR with possible RLL infiltrate.
   Hepatic encephalopathy unlikely given only mild elevation to LFTs. This
   is very unlikely to be meningitis acquired since admission to hospital,
   will hold off on LP for now and d/w neuro.
   - cont methylene blue and thiamine for [**Name (NI) 8017**] toxicity.
   - strict aspiration precautions
   - f/u neuro recs. Ask if still want to consider LP given clinical
   improvement.
   - f/u blood cx
   Aspiration pneumonitis: Patient was originally covered for hospital
   witnessed aspiration event. Found to have a fever. No infiltrates have
   been visualized on CXR. No leukocytosis. AMS improved on current
   treatment.  Aspiration PNA unlikely.
   - Given negative culture data and no signs of infection, will D/C
   vanc/Zosyn
   - strict aspiration precautions
   - Keep NPO.
   .
   NSVT: Patient had run of 13 beats of Vtach in the setting of
   hypokalemia and hypomag.
   - replete lytes
   - monitor on tele
   # Hyperchloremic Non gap metabolic acidosis with hypokalemia: likely
   secondary to NS fluid resuscitation with chemotherapy treatment.
   - will continue to trend on AM/PM lytes
   - Continue LR @ 75 cc/hr
   .
   # Follicular Cell Lymphoma: Pt with recurrent disease after initial
   treatment with RCHOP, she was admitted for induction with ICE+study
   [**Doctor Last Name **] in protocol regimen.  Pt was tolerating regimen well until today
   when she developped acute MS changes.  Now concern for [**Doctor Last Name 8017**]
   neurotoxicity, methylene blue indicated and safe at 6GPD levels NL.
   - chemo regimen complete, continue aggressive hydration
   - start methylene blue 50mg q6hr for [**Doctor Last Name 8017**] neurotoxicity
   - f/u BMT recs
   - Continue to treat associated nausea with zofran prn / compazine prn
   - Ask BMT about initiation of Neupogen
   .
   # Transaminitis: Patient has a mild transaminitis and elevated LDH
   likely due to chemo regimen and lysis of lymphoma cells.  MS changes
   unlikely due to hepatic encephalopathy but will check ammonia
   - continue to trend LFTs
   - f/u ammonia level
   .

   complete details. In brief, 87 yoF w/ h/o R heart failure, severe TR,
   severe pulmonary htn, PAF who was admitted [**12-30**] with presyncope and
   nausea after having her lopressor increased and diltiazem added several
   weeks ago for AF. She has had poor po intake, decreased UOP since
   discharge [**12-10**]. On admission, O2 sat 80%, INR 9.7, Cr 2.6 (from 1.4),
   CXR clear. She has been given ~ 4L IVF over course of the day. O2
   pleths have been unreliable throughout day although blood gas earlier
   in day with PaO2 of 133. This evening, repeat ABG performed due to
   persistently poor pleth revealed PaO2 41 with lactate 4. She was placed
   on NRB and transferred to CCU. Currently, she denies any current SOB.
   She notes her breathing feels much better than on admission. She denies
   any SOB at rest. No current CP, LH. Lengthy discussion held with
   patient regarding escalation of care with intubation and resuscitation
   if necessary and she was clear that she would not want CPR, electric
   shocks, or intubation.
   O: 96.7, 98/65, 53, 16, 90% NRB
   elderly, resting comfortably, no tachypnea, accessory muscle use
   JVP to angle of jaw sitting at 60 degrees with prominent V wave
   irreg irreg. II/VI <> sys murmur at LUSB. II/VI early sys murmur at
   LLSB and apex
   CTAB
   S/NT/ND
   Cool extremities. Faint DP pulses B.
   Labs reviewed. Repeat ABG in ICU on NRB with PaO2 60. Lactate improved
   to 3. INR 10.8. Cr worsened again:  2.6->1.6->1.4. CXR without frank
   pulmonary edema. ECG AF with V rate 42. Diffuse low voltage. Nl axis.
   Diffuse TW flattening. Compared to prior [**2141-12-19**], HR is slower.
   A/P: 87 yoF w/ R heart failure, severe TR, severe pulmonary htn, PAF
   admitted with presyncope and nausea in the setting of uptitration of
   nodal agents and poor po intake now with unexplained hypoxia,
   hypotension, bradycardia, ARF, and supratherapeutic INR.
   Regarding her hypoxia, the cause is unclear. Worsened since admission.
   Main intervention has been IVF expansion but little evidence to suggest
   pulmonary edema. Suspect some contribution of severe pulmonary
   hypertension although would not explain acute worsening. Possibly
   related to R->L shunting from increased R sided filling pressures with
   volume expansion.
   Regarding her hypotension, bradycardia, and ARF, all presumed due to
   decreased po intake and increase in nodal agents 2 weeks ago. BPs
   improved after 4L IVF. HRs remains slow but presyncopal symptoms have
   improved. Unclear why Cr so variable during admission. Rare urine eos
   seen and urine Na 62 so may not be entirely prerenal in etiology.

   but might worsen left sided filling given RV failure, TR, and pulm htn
   and unclear if will improve oxygenation dramatically w/o e/o pulm edema
   or underlying COPD.
   - cont high flow O2
   - consider trial of vasopressors to increase left sided afterload to

   shunting

                                 FINAL REPORT

 This is a 60-year-old man with end-stage renal disease. Hemodialysis
 dependent, cirrhosis admitted for VATS decortication of left lung effusion now
 with poor flow in the previously placed hemodialysis catheter.

 After the patient was imaged under fluoroscopy it was determined that the kink
 in the previously placed catheter from the right internal jugular vein was
 inserted too high in the neck thereby creating an acute bend in the catheter
 which kinked. The kink is the reason for poor flow and because of this the
 catheter was removed. A new internal jugular puncture was made under
 ultrasound control approximately 2 cm above the right clavicle. The new tunnel
 was made lateral to the previous  tunnel site.  T he new Angiodynamics
 catheter (23 cm tip to cuff) was tunneled to the internal jugular puncture
 site. The  guidewire and microcatheter in the jugular vein  was exchanged for
 an .038 wire and the soft tissue tract into the jugular vein was dilated to a
 9 F size followed by placement of the peel- away sheath. The guide wire and
 internal stylete was removed from the peel-away sheath and the tunnel dialysis
 catheter placed in the right atrium. The long tip of the dialysis catheter was
 placed in the right atrium with the short limb at the junction of the right
 atrium and superior vena cava. There was excellent flow. Single stitch was
 placed in the region of the jugular puncture and the dialysis catheter sutured
 to maintain placement.

 CONCLUSION:
 1. Removal of previously placed dialysis catheter because of  inadequate
 function.
 2. Replacement with a new catheter satisfactory for immediate dialysis.

 prominent right PICA.  Selective injection of the right common carotid artery
 demonstrates normal cervical course without evidence of dissection and smooth
 appearing carotid bifurcation without evidence of atherosclerosis.  The
 catheter was advanced in position within the right internal carotid artery.
 Selective injection of this artery demonstrates a normal cervical and
 intracranial course without evidence of aneurysm, fistula, or dissection.

 dissection as well as smooth appearing carotid bifurcation without evidence of

 carotid artery.  Selective injection of this artery demonstrates normal

 aorta, heart and pericardium are unremarkable.  The central pulmonary arteries
 enhance normally, without evidence of intraluminal thrombus.  The peripheral
 branches of the pulmonary arteries are not well evaluated on this study.

 lesions throughout the liver, likely simple cyst, but too small to
 definitively characterize.  The gallbladder is distended and appears to
 contain extravasation of contrast.  No secondary signs to suggest
 cholecystitis.

 resolving contusion.

 atelectasis/consolidation.

 cysts, but too small to characterize.

 it. No other CT findings to suggest cholecystitis; correlate clinically.

 Reason: RADIOLOGIST CALL BACK
 ______________________________________________________________________________
                                 FINAL REPORT
 HISTORY:  Radiologist call back.

 TECHNIQUE:  Multiplanar T1 and T2-weighted imaging of the cervical spine was
 obtained.
 FINDINGS:  Please note that the original dictation was lost in the PACS
 transcription archive- this is a redictation.

 Comparison with the prior study of [**6-6**] reveals improved image quality, and
 confirmation of the presence of a large, posteriorly situated epidural
 hematoma, which appears to extend from the C6-7 to approximately the T4 level
 of the spine. There is moderate cord compression, and likely a small amount of
 elevated T2 signal in the compressed cord, suggesting edema.

 There is also moderate prevertebral soft tissue swelling, again extending from
 the skull base as far distally as the C5 level. As it was apparent that the
 patient was taking Coumadin, and manifested an INR of 8, this radiological
 finding could certainly represent a prevertebral hematoma, as opposed to edema
 secondary to ligamentous disruption.

 The posteriorly situated paraspinal edema apparently relates to non-displaced
 fractures of the spinous processes of C5 and C6, not initially detected on the
 prior day's CT scan but confirmed upon review of this study. (Inquiry by
 telephone to the staff caring for the patient, immediately after this MR study
 was obtained,  to notify them of these fractures resulted in information
 indicating that the patient had been maintained in a hard cervical collar, up
 to the time of this MR study, thus minimizing any issues that might arise from
 potential mechanical instability of the spine from bony or ligamentous
 injuries.

 The mid-cervical spondylytic changes are again seen as well as  the elevated
 T2 signal patterns within the T2 and T3 vertebral bodies. Even upon reviewing
 the prior cervical CT scan, which extended as far caudally as T2, no fracture
 was seen involving that vertebral body.  Perhaps the abnormal T2 signal
 represented a bone bruise.  The right sided posterior paraspinal hemorrhages,
 seen on the prior MR study are better delineated at this time, likely due to
 the availability of T2- weighted axial scans.  However, these abnormal regions
 were seen on the prior MR [**Name13 (STitle) 26441**] sagittal T2 weighted images.

 CONCLUSION:  Complex multicompartmental spinal hemorrhages, including an
 epidural hemorrhage.  The findings of this study were communicated immediately
 to the trauma team caring for the patient following the conclusion of this
 examination.  As potential evacuation of the epidural hemorrhage was being
 contemplated, it was decided to obtain a follow up thoracic and lumbar spine
 imaging study to provide complete depiction of the spinal cord and cauda
 equina,  and rule out any other hemorrhages being present more distally.

                                                             (Over)

 pneumocephalus has slightly improved.

 The focal hypodensity in the left frontal lobe has somewhat increased in size

 attenuation has developed in the parafalcine left frontal lobe on series 2
 images 21 through at least 24. Again these findings could represent delayed
 hemorrhagic contusions or acute infarcts that had developed in the left
 anterior cerebral artery territory. If these do represent infarcts, they
 could be either arterial or venous in origin.

 There continues to be rightward midline shift of an unchanged amount. The
 lacune within the left thalamus is unchanged. There has been no change in the
 remainder of the examination.

 The right frontal subgaleal hematoma is unchanged.

 IMPRESSION:  The left frontal hypodensity has slightly increased in size.  The
 intraparenchymal hemorrhage has not changed.

 An additional area of hypodensity is also developed in the parafalcine frontal
 lobe.

 The combination of these findings could relate to an infarct.  Consideration
 should be given to the possibility of superficial venous infarcts.

 Alternatively, these could represent contusions.  The degree of midline shift
 is unchanged.  Tiny amounts of residual subdural hematoma remain over the left
 frontoparietal convexity as well as along the falx and tentorium.

 HISTORY:  32-year-old male with malpositioned PICC.

 RADIOLOGISTS:  Drs. [**Last Name (STitle) 769**] and [**Name5 (PTitle) 65**] performed the procedure.  Dr. [**Last Name (STitle) 65**],
 the attending radiologist, supervised.

 PROCEDURE AND FINDINGS:  A preprocedure timeout was performed using two
 patient identifiers.  The patient's left arm was prepped and draped in the
 usual sterile fashion.  The previously placed PICC in the left arm was noted
 to be malpositioned with termination in the left axillary vein.  A 0.018-inch
 guidewire was then inserted through the previously placed PICC and advanced
 into the SVC under fluoroscopic guidance.  The old PICC was exchanged for a
 4.5 French micropuncture sheath.  A new dual-lumen PICC was trimmed to
 appropriate length of 45 cm and advanced over the wire to a termination in the
 SVC under fluoroscopic guidance.  The peel-away sheath and guide wire were
 removed.  The PICC was flushed, capped and secured to the skin with a sterile
 dressing.  The patient tolerated the procedure well.

 IMPRESSION:  Successful PICC exchange over a wire with new dual-lumen 45 cm
 PICC terminating in the SVC.  The line is now ready for use.

 performed. There was no dilation of intrahepatic ducts, and mild dilation of
 the common bile duct was noticed.  The lower end of the common hepatic duct
 was anastomosed to the jejunum side by side.  Contrast flowed freely into and
 through the jejunum. There was no leaking of contrast noticed. A series of
 fluoroscopic images were taken, following the passage of the contrast inside
 the jejunum, and no contrast leak was identified.

 was made to just perform a percutaneous cholangiogram and drainage catheter

 lidocaine and lidocaine with epinephrine were also administered locally.

 PROCEDURE:  Informed consent was obtained outlining the risks and benefits of
 the procedure.  Following this, the patient was brought to the angiography
 suite and placed supine on the angiography table.  Preprocedure ultrasound was
 performed.  The abdomen was prepped and draped in the usual sterile fashion.
 A preprocedure huddle and timeout were performed as per [**Hospital1 11**] protocol.  Scout
 images were recorded.  Ultrasound was used to identify a suitable location for
 peritoneal drain placement.  The skin was anesthetized with 1% lidocaine and a
 19-gauge access needle was passed obliquely into the peritoneal cavity.  A
 0.035 J-tip wire was advanced into the peritoneal cavity under fluoroscopic
 guidance.  After making a small skin incision, the access site was dilated
 with 8 and 12 French dilators and a 16 French peel-away sheath was then
 advanced over the wire.  Attention was then turned to creation of the
 subcutaneous tunnel.  A suitable site, 7 cm posterosuperior to the peritoneal
 access point, was identified.  1% lidocaine and 1% lidocaine with epinephrine
 was used to anesthetize the tract. The 14 French Pleurx catheter was tunneled
 through the skin entry point to the peritoneal access site.  The catheter was
 then advanced through the peel-away sheath to lie across the midline in the
 pelvis.  The peritoneal access point was sutured with a 4-0 Vicryl
 subcuticular suture and Steri-Strips were applied.  The Pleurx catheter was
 secured to the skin with a 0 silk anchor suture.  A large sterile dressing was
 applied.  There were no immediate complications.  Following the procedure, 3
 liters of ascites was drained prior to transfer of the patient back to the

 preprocedure timeout and huddle were performed per [**Hospital1 184**] protocol.

 Using sterile technique and 1% lidocaine, the right common femoral artery was
 punctured with a 19 gauge needle under fluoroscopic and palpatory guidance.  A
 .035 [**Last Name (un) 89**] wire was advanced into the abdominal aorta under fluoroscopic
 guidance.  The needle was exchanged for a 5 French vascular sheath with the
 side arm attached to heparinized saline.  A 5 French [**Last Name (un) 4851**] catheter was
 used to select the celiac axis and subsequently the left gastric artery
 (previously embolized) which was further selectively catheterized using a
 Renegade HI-[**Last Name (un) **] catheter and 0.01 to 0.018 Transcend guidewire.  Next the
 gastroduodenal artery was selectively cannulated with the combination of the
 Renegade HI-[**Last Name (un) **] catheter and Transcend microwire.  An angiogram revealed
 extravasation in a branch from the mid right gastroepiploic in the left
 parasagittal plane overlying the greater curvature of distended stomach. Using
 a combination of the Renegade HI-[**Last Name (un) **] catheter and Transcend wire the mid right
 gastroepiploic was selected and two Cook .018 1 cm x 2 mm Hilal coils were
 deployed.  A Gelfoam slurry was next injected to near stasis.

 Next, attention was turned to the superior mesenteric artery.  The [**Last Name (un) 4851**]
 catheter was used to perform a SMA angiogram.  Using a combination of the
 Renegade HI-[**Last Name (un) **] catheter and Transcend guidewire, the right colic artery was
 selectively cannulated and a selective angiogram obtained.  Next attention was
 directed to the inferior mesenteric artery, which was also cannulated using
 the [**Last Name (un) 4851**] 5 French catheter before arteriography.

 Catheters and wires were removed.  The 5 French [**Last Name (un) 67**]-Tip vascular sheath was
 removed and manual pressure held for 20 minutes to obtain hemostasis.  The
 patient tolerated the procedure well and there were no immediate post-

 within the abdominal vasculature.

 identified.

 leak (no mediastinal hematoma).  Limited evaluation for dissection given the
 lack of IV contrast.

 mild pulmonary hypertension.

 atelectasis.  No consolidation to suggest pneumonia.
 4.  Bilateral rib fractures, chronic and acute.  No pneumothorax.

 INDICATION:  78-year-old man with bleeding from the external auditory canal
 after head trauma, and known SAH and SDH; evaluate for temporal bone fracture.

 COMPARISON:  CT of the head without contrast, [**2113-6-9**].

 TECHNIQUE:  Helical axial 0.625mm MDCT images were acquired through the
 temporal bones without intravenous contrast.  Sagittal, coronal and oblique
 (Stenvers and [**Last Name (un) 41550**] imaging planes) reformations were generated and reviewed
 on a separate workstation.

 FINDINGS:  There is a longitudinal fracture of the right temporal bone
 extending from the petrous portion, likely to the squamous portion, better
 visualized in the axial images (2:12).  There is opacification of the major
 portion of the right mastoid air cells and the external auditory canals, the
 middle ear cavity.  The ossicles appear intact.  No fractures are identified
 in the left temporal bone.  Minimal soft tissue is seen within the left
 external auditory canal, likely impacted cerumen.  There is diffuse
 opacification of the ethmoidal air cells, bilaterally, with an air-fluid level
 in the left maxillary sinus.  Minimal mucosal thickening is seen within the
 right maxillary sinus and the sphenoid air cells.

 IMPRESSION:  Longitudinal fracture through the right petrous temporal bone.
 No evidence of ossicular disruption.  Opacification of the right mastoid air
 cells, external auditory canal and middle ear cavity.

 NOTE ADDED IN ATTENDING REVIEW: The right temporal bone fracture is comminuted
 and complex, with extensive involvement of its mastoid segment. A fracture
 component traverses the middle ear cavity, where it involves the ossicular
 chain. While the malleus and incus appear to maintain a normal relationship,
 there is evidence of incudo-stapedial dissociation, with likely fracture of
 the stapes superstructure, and the stapes footplate appears displaced from the
 oval window; these findings are best-appreciated on the specialized
 reformations. The fracture appears to spare the otic capsule. A fracture
 component does exit at the glenoid fossa, but there is no evidence of
 subluxation of the TMJ.

 (interventional radiologist) was present and supervising throughout the entire

 MEDICATIONS:  The procedure was initiated after the induction of general
 anesthesia.  1% lidocaine was used for local pain control.

 TECHNIQUE:  After discussion of the risks, benefits and alternatives to the
 procedure, written informed consent was obtained.  The patient was brought to
 the angiography suite and placed supine on the imaging table.  The right upper
 abdomen was prepped and draped in usual sterile fashion.  A preprocedure
 timeout and huddle were performed per [**Hospital 51**] medical protocol.

 Under fluoroscopic guidance, an AccuStick needle was sequentially introduced
 into the liver and withdrawn with concomitant injection of dilute contrast.
 After opacification of a nondilated right hepatic duct, a headhunter guidewire
 was advanced into the lower common bile duct.  The inner portion of the
 Accustick system was introduced into the CBD.  Contrast injection confirmed
 location.  A 0.035 superstiff glide was advanced into the common bile duct.  A
 6 French [**Last Name (un) 169**] Tip sheath was introduced.  Using a combination of a 5-French
 Kumpe catheter and glidewire, the papillae was traversed.  The Kumpe catheter
 and guidewire was advanced into the more distal duodenum.  The glide was
 exchanged for a 0.035 superstiff Amplatz.  The sheath was removed, and an 8.5
 French Cook catheter advanced under fluoroscopic guidance.  The locking
 pigtail loop was formed and the pigtail retracted into optimal position
 confirmed by contrast injection.  The catheter was attached using [**Initials (NamePattern4) **] [**Last Name (NamePattern4) **]
 sandal-type suture with 0 silk.  A bag was attached.  Sterile dressings were
 applied.  The patient tolerated the procedure well and was returned to the
 ICU.

Infant is a FT, 3690 FT male newborn who was admitted to the NICU for concerns of possible stridor.

Infant was born to a 21 y.o. G1 P0 to 1 mother.  Serologies: O+, ab neg, hep neg, RPR NR, RI, GBS neg, GC/Chl/PPD neg.  Prognancy was uncomplicated. Ther is a report of Gonnorhea during pregnancy which was treated and mother now tests negative.

Mother presented in spontaneous labor. Proceeded to vaginal delivery. +meconium. Not intubated as infant cried soon after delivery. However, infant after cries stopped crying with no spontaneous respirations requiring PPV for several breaths with good response.  Apgars 4,8.  In DR, infant thought to have stridor with vigorous crying.  Transported to NICU for evaluation.

Other sepsis risks: No maternal fever, ROM > 48 hours, +intrapartum abx for almost 24 hours.

Currently on exam:

Infant appears very comfortable without respiratory distress, no GFR, no stridor. When infant cries vigorously slight hoarseness to cry, and high-pitched inspiration but not stridor.  AFSF. +Molding. Intact palate with good vigorous suck. Neck without masses. Lungs CTA, =, no stridor audible with stethoscope. CV RRR, no murmur, 2+ FP. Abd soft, +BS. GU nl phallus, testes down bilat. Patent anus, no sacral anomalies, stable hips, ext pink and well perfused. Symmetrical Moro.

Impression:
1.  AGA, FT male newborn.
2.  r/o stridor - current exam does not support stridor. Does have a very slight hoarse cry and high pitched inspiration with vigorous crying.  Infant is without any distress from this.
3.  No sepsis risk factors (besides ROM > 24 hours).

Plan:
1.  Infant has been observed and he demonstrates no distress. Sats 100% in RA.  If tolerates feeding without instability, will transfer to NBN for further care.
2.  Infant without significant sepsis risk factors.  will not send lab work at this time. If clinical course changes will proceed with sepsis evaluation at that time.
